text: little women
lung
hi everyone anthony fantano here the
internet's
busiest music nerd and it's time for a
review of the new little women album
lung this is the sophomore full-length
effort from new york jazz noise
improvisational avant-garde music outfit
little women and all these genres
combined together with some very
intricate math rock grooves made this
band's debut lp in 2010 really dense
difficult to make heads or tails of but
still some real moments of beauty and
some great playing shine through these
very tough moments and made this album
one of my favorite lps in 2010. i was
absolutely psyched to see the band
return with a new full length a new
piece
if you will and instead of parsing it
out into different tracks like they did
on their last full length they have
presented listeners with one
42-minute long track on this new album
the recording on this new lp feels
roughly the same as the last one more of
an emphasis on technique and playing
than trippy or distorted effects it
feels very intimate freewheeling kind of
in the moment really letting the rawness
of the guitar the tenor and also
saxophones and the drums speak for
themselves this new lp just like the
band's last full length is a
multi-faceted piece for sure but i guess
the question is do the pieces on this
new lp also come together into something
that is thrilling moving exciting as
well the lp throat was never the most
avant-garde thing on the block it was
never meant to be artists like john zorn
i feel like push weirdness much further
to me the album throat was kind of a
balance between composition and chaos
and for sure lung also tries to find its
own combination of those two
characteristics as well this lp kicks
things off with an intro that features
very light drums sparse guitar serene
harmonized saxophone phrasing it's seven
minutes or so of just rock jazz bliss
but then all of a sudden these stringy
lanky
weird mutated guitar chords come
crashing down with drums and everything
in terms of just
goes right away the music all of a
sudden becomes very jagged and very
cruel to the listener with just its its
oddness then after this comes these long
spans of
chords and melodies
intervals that it seems like the
saxophones dance around in this very
tribal primal way
with how they move with one another and
interact with one another it's almost as
if they come closer together in terms of
harmony and and drift apart as the band
trips through these pieces meanwhile
guitars and drums are just providing
very light quiet backdrops and the only
thing separating these different parts
from one another are the occasional jazz
freak out that lasts for a very short
amount of time and just comes in and
jars me for a few moments it's a sort of
cruel joke that the band punches at the
listener with these very loud moments
like a merciless bully and then right
afterwards the saxophones return to
dancing around some musical phrases very
quietly again but each time going for a
sort of different musical vibe sometimes
sounding very soft pretty calming others
dissonant and then again fiery this goes
on until about the halfway point of the
album where the band really introduces
the mother of all freakouts on this
entire lp which is one of the most
jaw-droppingly intense moments on this
album i'm too jar the listener feels
like it might have been the intention
and to go back to this album and listen
to it again and again these jarring
moments become so much less surprising
or moving because it's kind of like you
know you know when the shark's gonna
jump out of the water
though the quiet parts may feel very
pretty it's not like they build or
evolve into anything that that really
sort of touches me an emotional way the
stringy jagged guitars that occur
earlier in the album end up showing up
later as well bringing somewhat of a
theme to this album some consistency i'm
hearing pieces again there is kind of a
circular quality to this composition the
band has pulled together and maybe
people will gravitate toward that more
than some of the stuff that the band put
on their full-length debut which can
kind of feel like this disjointed linear
musical experience even though i like
that the band is trying to build this
piece with a more consistent structure
i'm not really all that enamored with
the pieces that this structure is built
out of it seems like many of these
louder more abrasive moments that come
on very suddenly all function on the
same
techniques and ideas coming from each
player really the only interesting
moment that came out of these abrasive
spots on the album was the final
ascension of the album which really
really hits a high mark in terms of just
volume and intensity ear piercing howls
coming from the saxes stuttering guitars
and very busy drums all over the place
it's like this album is trying to
oppositely mirror the very friendly
beginning that this lp started off with
honestly this sophomore full-length
didn't really take me on the emotional
ride that the debut did while i'm still
into the production i think the playing
is pretty solid and that the way the
band likes to create just a very
intimate recording around their stuff i
just think they put a little bit too
much of an emphasis on
putting parts in this album that would
grab the listener and shake them
violently and then just sort of put them
back down in their place and you know
pet them a little bit and then grab the
gun and shake them
meanwhile in the midst of these moments
where they're not being shaken things
are just you know feeling
all right very few spots on this album
filled me with wonder especially from a
melodic perspective i
for the most part really just stayed
intrigued
and that's about it i'm kind of feeling
a light to decent six
on this thing if you've given it a
listen what did you think of it did you
